<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>Dynovare Improvement Report</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Calibri, Arial, sans-serif;
      color: #1f2937;
      line-height: 1.5;
      margin: 40px;
    }
    h1, h2 {
      color: #0b3c5d;
      margin-bottom: 8px;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: 26pt;
    }
    h2 {
      font-size: 16pt;
      margin-top: 26px;
    }
    p {
      margin: 8px 0 12px;
    }
    ul {
      margin: 8px 0 12px 22px;
    }
    li {
      margin: 6px 0;
    }
    .intro {
      font-size: 11.5pt;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Dynovare Improvement Report</h1>
  <p class="intro">
    Dynovare has been transformed into a much more complete policy intelligence and drafting platform.
    The product now supports a stronger end-to-end workflow that connects public discovery, private drafting,
    AI-assisted improvement, critique, simulation, revision, and polished export in one experience.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Public Discovery and Platform Presence</h2>
  <p>
    The public side of Dynovare now feels like a serious product rather than a simple landing experience.
    The homepage was redesigned with stronger storytelling, clearer value communication, richer visual structure,
    and more credible product framing. Dedicated About, Contact, and FAQ pages were added, and the footer and
    navigation were expanded into a more complete public information architecture.
  </p>
  <p>
    This strengthens the beginning of the user journey. A visitor can now understand what the platform does,
    explore public intelligence, and move naturally into deeper workflows.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Public Repository, Rankings, and State Intelligence</h2>
  <p>
    The repository and rankings experience was substantially improved. Public policy records can now be browsed
    with stronger filtering, cleaner taxonomy, and better presentation. Rankings were refined into a more useful
    policy intelligence layer, helping users identify stronger public policy examples and compare signals across records.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Nigeria map is now a core discovery tool. It moved from a basic placeholder into a proper state-based map
    that appears across public and internal experiences, supports richer interaction, and helps users move from geography
    to evidence to action more naturally.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Signed-In Workspace and Private Policy Flow</h2>
  <p>
    One of the most important workflow improvements is the separation between public intelligence and private work.
    Uploaded policies and AI-generated drafts are now stored under the user’s workspace instead of being pushed into
    the general repository. Signed-in users also now have their own repository experience, so they can explore public
    policy examples without leaving the signed-in workspace context.
  </p>
  <p>
    Public policies can be pulled into the workspace as editable private copies. That allows users to start from
    strong public examples and then work on them privately inside their own drafting and review flow.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Policy Studio and AI Drafting</h2>
  <p>
    Dynovare now has a much stronger policy drafting workflow. AI generation no longer ends as a plain output file.
    It creates a structured in-app draft that opens in Policy Studio, where the user can continue editing section by section.
    Draft generation accepts richer briefing inputs such as goals, context, constraints, references, domain, energy source,
    and optional target length.
  </p>
  <p>
    The generation system itself was expanded significantly. It now produces fuller policy structure, stronger implementation
    detail, better drafting guidance, and evidence-backed output. It also uses an iterative expansion flow so longer document
    requests can be pushed closer to the requested size instead of stopping too early.
  </p>

  <h2>5. AI Critique Workflow</h2>
  <p>
    The critique experience is now much deeper and more workflow-oriented. Instead of producing only a basic score, critique now
    gives users a richer policy review including executive verdicts, readiness signals, decision recommendations, maturity profiles,
    evidence gaps, stakeholder impacts, priority actions, strengths, risks, and implementation outlook.
  </p>
  <p>
    This changes critique from a passive scoring step into an active revision tool. Users can see what is weak, why it matters,
    and what to improve next.
  </p>

  <h2>6. AI Policy Improvement Loop</h2>
  <p>
    Dynovare now supports a stronger critique-to-revision loop. Users can generate improved versions of policies using critique findings,
    and those improved drafts are saved back into the workspace as editable policy records. That means the platform now supports a real
    “review and improve” cycle rather than a one-time critique step.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Simulation and Scenario Modeling</h2>
  <p>
    Simulation has been expanded into a more decision-support-oriented workflow. Users can define scenario inputs such as horizon,
    adoption, implementation strength, funding level, and assumptions, then receive richer outputs such as access impact, reliability,
    emissions change, risk, cost range, readiness, cost drivers, critical risks, enabling actions, beneficiary outlook, and year-by-year projections.
  </p>
  <p>
    Results are saved into workspace history and can be revisited later, which makes simulation useful not only as a one-time check,
    but also as part of iterative policy development.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Workspace Memory and Continuity</h2>
  <p>
    The platform now retains and surfaces more of the user’s working history. Dashboard summaries, recent activity, critique timelines,
    simulation timelines, uploaded policies, and draft records have all been strengthened so users can continue their work over time
    instead of treating each tool as a disconnected single-use screen.
  </p>
  <p>
    This makes Dynovare feel much more like a real workspace with continuity and much less like a set of isolated pages.
  </p>

  <h2>9. Design System and Product Quality</h2>
  <p>
    The overall interface quality was substantially improved across both public and internal pages. Layouts, cards, typography, motion,
    spacing, color usage, and iconography were all upgraded into a more polished design system. The product now feels more intentional,
    more premium, and more trustworthy for policy teams and institutional users.
  </p>
  <p>
    Branding is more consistent, the map is more integrated, metric cards are more stable, and signed-in users remain inside signed-in flows
    more reliably. These improvements collectively make the platform feel more coherent and more product-grade.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Export and Delivery</h2>
  <p>
    Export now behaves more like the final stage of a proper policy workflow. Instead of immediately turning AI output into a static document,
    Dynovare now treats export as something that happens after drafting, critique, simulation, and revision. Styled PDF export sits at the end
    of the workflow, where it can reflect more mature policy content.
  </p>

  <h2>11. PWA and Product Installability</h2>
  <p>
    Dynovare now supports a stronger app-like experience with PWA installability, manifest configuration, app icons, metadata improvements,
    and a smoother install prompt flow. This makes the platform feel more like a modern deployable product and helps users keep it easily accessible.
  </p>

  <h2>12. Overall Workflow Impact</h2>
  <p>
    The most important improvement is that the platform now behaves like a connected policy workflow rather than a collection of disconnected tools.
    A user can discover public signals, import a policy into a private workspace, draft or generate content, critique it, simulate likely outcomes,
    revise based on those findings, and export a polished final output without breaking the working flow.
  </p>
  <p>
    In practical workflow terms, Dynovare now supports:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Starting from public policy intelligence and state-level signals</li>
    <li>Moving selected policies into a private working environment</li>
    <li>Generating long-form editable policy drafts</li>
    <li>Using AI critique to identify structural and implementation weaknesses</li>
    <li>Running simulation to stress-test assumptions and outcomes</li>
    <li>Improving drafts iteratively with AI and manual editing</li>
    <li>Exporting a more polished, decision-ready document at the end</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Overall, the platform is now much closer to a full policy intelligence and drafting system than a simple policy viewer or document generator.
  </p>
</body>
</html>
